         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers1013">
               <p>Originally an innkeeper in <placeName>Alnwick</placeName>, Hindmarsh was appointed
                  as writing tutor, and his wife <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1014.xml"
                     />Phillis (Laing) Hindmarsh</persName> (<date from="1731" to="1797"
                     >1731–97</date>) as housekeeper, at Kingswood school by the <date when="1766"
                     >1766</date> Conference. James served there until <date when="1771"
                  >1771</date>, when he was admitted &apos;on trial&apos; as a preacher. He was
                  granted full connection in <date when="1773">1773</date>, and traveled until
                     <date>1783</date>. In <date when="1785">1785</date> he left the Methodists to
                  join his son <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1015.xml"/>Robert</persName> with
                  the Swedenborgians. See <hi rend="italic">Works</hi>, 10:319, 415, 531; and <hi
                     rend="italic">WHS</hi> 7 (<date when="1909">1909</date>): 66–67.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
